Rating: 4
The best prep time/result ratio I've ever seen on a pasta that's beyond spaghetti and marinara sauce! An easy way to combine great ingredients often found in much more complicated dishes. Makes a great presentation, and the foolproof sauce is one of the cleverest I have ever seen. I doubled my olives (a house favorite) but cut corners on the salt where I could, adding no extra and using low sodium chicken broth. Perfect result. Another great thing about this recipe is that it lends itself to endless ingredient variations which do not change the prep much... definitely a winner and very popular with the guests!

Rating: 4
I made a few small changes. Cut the oil back to about a tablespoon, used about 1/2 cup of onions and 1/2 cup sundried tomatoes, a pinch of dried oregano, an extra clove of garlic, a 1/4 cup of sherry and a cup of left over chicken, chopped. One tip for the oil overload is to squeeze the sun dried tomatoes between multiple paper towels to remove some oil. Oh, I also used 1/3 lb mini-penne (what I had on hand) and used my own homemade salt-free broth which I keep in the freezer in varying portions. By the time the pasta was done the chicken, veggie mix was coated with all the sauce, with none sitting in the pan, so I was worried there would not be enough sauce when the pasta was added. I made the goat cheese sauce as directed and added it with the pasta and it was all sauced perfectly. I was really surprised how creamy and smooth it turned out. It was just as good as alfredo, but the goat cheese has alot less calories than all that cream and butter. Fabulous meal that will be made again.

